\begin_layout Subsection
Motes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Motes are the small shards of the Dream's power that a Hopeful draws on
 to fuel her magic.
 She does not need to gather it from an outside source, but rather simply
 draws them from deep within her soup.
 A Luminous may simply spend a certain number of Motes equal to her Mote
 Capacity safely each turn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond that, she must draw deeper on her being, converting a small fragment
 of her own emotions and dreams to fuel the rest of that magic and leaving
 her feeling down and worn out until she has had the time to recover.
 When her Mote Capacity is exhausted, she may still intentionally take a
 box of mild Hope damage to spend an additional Mote for the turn.
 Should she have no remaining undamaged Hope boxes, she may take a box of
 severe Hope damage instead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike most types of supernatural creatures, a Princess cannot spend the
 Motes to use her powers over multiple turns.
 If a power costs more Motes than her Mote Capacity, she must spend it all
 in one turn and take the resulting Hope damage.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Invocations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ideals of each of the Dream Kingdoms resonate throughout the Dream,
 and Weavers draw on those Invocations to shape their own magics.
 Learning an Invocation allows a Luminous to draw on the pooled knowledge
 and magical skills that like-minded Luminous left behind generations ago.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Luminous may have up to 5 dots in each Invocation.
 Each Kingdom favors one Invocation, and the Luminous find the Invocation
 of their home Kingdom the easiest to learn.
 Due to this tie with the Dream Kingdoms that embody their beliefs, the
 Invocations are described under the Kingdom that they originate in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These Invocations reflect a worldview as much a source of power.
 While a Luminous can use the power of Kingdoms she does not agree with,
 she does grasp their logic and concepts intuitively and cannot draw on
 the Dream directly to learn them.
 As a guideline, a Luminous who agrees with one or two of an Invocation's
 Beliefs may intuitively learn three dots of it alone.
 One who agrees with all of them in at least vague terms may learn five
 dots of it alone.
 Otherwise, she must be taught the Invocation by someone who already understands
 its principles better.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regalia, Domains and Charms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Luminous magic is roughly divided into three major categories: Regalia,
 Domains and Charms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Regalia are the most physical embodiments of a Luminous' power.
 They are the radiant auras and weapons she summons in their Dream Form
 to fight or solve the kinds of problems that require a more direct approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Hopeful's Domains are the elements and concepts that resonate with her
 Invocations and her own dream.
 They are the power that defines the Luminous as fundamentally magical in
 the way they so often seem to be, allowing them to wield the elements as
 naturally as they move their own body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Charms are the more specialized powers of the Luminous, specific spells
 that allow them to touch upon the more esoteric mysteries of the world
 – or perhaps even create some of those mysteries themselves.
\end_layout

