\end_inset


\series bold
Component Skills:
\series default
 Empathy, Socialize, Animal Ken
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transformed Traits 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to their different set of attributes and skills, Luminous use different
 traits in their Dream Form and Mundane Form.
 In her dream form, she calculates derived attributes as such:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Luminous' Dream Form always has a default Size of 5, regardless of her
 natural size.
 They have separate Form Merits that may be used to change this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Maximum Willpower is calculated as Resistance + Finesse.
 Unlike with most of these traits, this total is used for her mundane form
 as well as her Dream Form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Defense is equal to the lower of her Resistance and Finesse + Flow.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initiative is equal to Finesse + Resistance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Speed is equal to Power + Finesse + 5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Form-Locked Dots 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Luminous may buy dots in her transformed attributes or skills directly,
 instead of increasing the corresponding mundane traits.
 Furthermore, she may buy dots in merits that only apply to one of her forms.
 Refund one beat for each experience spent on such a form-locked merit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Add your character's transformed attribute and skill dots to the normal
 base ranking derived from her mundane skills.
 As a Luminous' mundane attribute cap never increases, such dots are the
 only way for her to gain attributes and skills above 5 dots.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dual Identity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hopeful derive one last benefit from their transformation: Their mundane
 and dream forms appear to be two different people.
 Regardless of how similar her two forms look, others around her treat them
 as if they had entirely different appearances.
 This is not exactly an illusion, as it does not change what people see.
 Rather, it simply prevents them from recognizing the two forms as the same
 based on such.
 This protection extends to magical senses such as a Vampire's taste for
 blood, or an Uratha's ability to track others by scent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Supernatural powers used to try and link her two identities are similarly
 fooled.
 Powers that use Sympathy or Intimacy treat her two forms as separate --
 a friend who only knows her in her mundane form has no Sympathy with her
 Dream Form.
 Powers that determine information about a Luminous do not directly reveal
 information that connect her two identities, treating her (at best) as
 two people with close ties to the same friend group.
 That may still break her cover in the context of a full investigation,
 of course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As powerful as it is, however, a Luminous cannot rely solely on Dual Identity
 to protect herself.
 It does not prevent others from suspecting a Luminou' nature based on circumsta
ntial evidence.
 She cannot simply dip into a closet only to return as a mysterious magical
 girl, and not expect others to not draw the connection.
 She obviously cannot transform in front of someone, and expect Dual Identity
 to protect her even slightly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In cases where she needs to intentionally prove her identity, she may spend
 a Willpower to drop this protection for the rest of a scene.
 This does not necessarily convince others that she is the same person if
 she looks radically different in her two forms, but it at least removes
 any supernatural components of her disguise.
\end_layout

